    {
      "content": "How does Azure back up virtual machines?",
      "pos": [
        1031,
        1071
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the Azure Backup service initiates a backup job at the scheduled time, it triggers the backup extension to take a point-in-time snapshot.",
      "pos": [
        1072,
        1214
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This snapshot is taken in coordination with the Volume Shadow Copy Service (VSS) to get a consistent snapshot of the disks in the virtual machine without having to shut it down.",
      "pos": [
        1215,
        1392
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the snapshot is taken, the data is transferred by the Azure Backup service to the backup vault.",
      "pos": [
        1394,
        1495
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To make the backup process more efficient, the service identifies and transfers only the blocks of data that have changed since the last backup.",
      "pos": [
        1496,
        1640
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure virtual machine backup architecture",
      "pos": [
        1644,
        1685
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the data transfer is complete, the snapshot is removed and a recovery point is created.",
      "pos": [
        1753,
        1845
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Data consistency",
      "pos": [
        1851,
        1867
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Backing up and restoring business critical data is complicated by the fact that it needs to be backed up while the applications that produce the data are running.",
      "pos": [
        1868,
        2030
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To address this, Azure Backup provides application-consistent backups for Microsoft workloads by using VSS to ensure that data is written correctly to storage.",
      "pos": [
        2031,
        2190
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        2193,
        2333
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> For Linux virtual machines, only file-consistent backups are possible, since Linux does not have an equivalent platform to VSS."
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Backup takes VSS full backups on Windows VMs (read more about <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>VSS full backup<ept id=\"p1\">](http://blogs.technet.com/b/filecab/archive/2008/05/21/what-is-the-difference-between-vss-full-backup-and-vss-copy-backup-in-windows-server-2008.aspx)</ept>).",
      "pos": [
        2335,
        2572
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To enable VSS copy backups, the below registry key needs to be set on the VM.",
      "pos": [
        2573,
        2650
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This table explains the types of consistency and the conditions that they occur under during Azure VM backup and restore procedures.",
      "pos": [
        2738,
        2870
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consistency",
      "pos": [
        2874,
        2885
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "VSS-based",
      "pos": [
        2888,
        2897
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Explanation and details",
      "pos": [
        2900,
        2923
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Application consistency",
      "pos": [
        2966,
        2989
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Yes",
      "pos": [
        2992,
        2995
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is the ideal consistency type for Microsoft workloads as it ensures that:",
      "pos": [
        2998,
        3076
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The VM <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>boots up<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        3085,
        3103
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>no corruption<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        3108,
        3133
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>no data loss<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        3138,
        3162
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The data is consistent to the application that uses the data, by involving the application at the time of backup--using VSS.",
      "pos": [
        3167,
        3291
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Most Microsoft workloads have VSS writers that do workload-specific actions that are related to data consistency.",
      "pos": [
        3297,
        3410
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, Microsoft SQL Server has a VSS writer that ensures that the writes to the transaction log file and the database are done correctly.",
      "pos": [
        3411,
        3555
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For Azure VM backups, getting an application-consistent recovery point means that the backup extension was able to invoke the VSS workflow and complete it <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>correctly<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> before the VM snapshot was taken.",
      "pos": [
        3564,
        3764
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Naturally, this means that the VSS writers of all the applications in the Azure VM have been invoked as well.",
      "pos": [
        3765,
        3874
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "(Learn the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>basics of VSS<ept id=\"p1\">](http://blogs.technet.com/b/josebda/archive/2007/10/10/the-basics-of-the-volume-shadow-copy-service-vss.aspx)</ept> and dive deep into the details of <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>how it works<ept id=\"p2\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc785914%28v=ws.10%29.aspx)</ept>).",
      "pos": [
        3882,
        4134
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "File-system consistency",
      "pos": [
        4139,
        4162
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Yes - for Windows-based computers",
      "pos": [
        4165,
        4198
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are two scenarios where the recovery point can be <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>file-system consistent<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>:",
      "pos": [
        4201,
        4282
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Backups of Linux VMs in Azure, since Linux does not have an equivalent platform to VSS.",
      "pos": [
        4290,
        4377
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "VSS failure during backup for Windows VMs in Azure.",
      "pos": [
        4381,
        4432
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In both these cases, the best that can be done is to ensure that:",
      "pos": [
        4443,
        4508
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The VM <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>boots up<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4518,
        4536
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>no corruption<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4541,
        4566
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>no data loss<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4570,
        4594
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Applications need to implement their own \"fix-up\" mechanism on the restored data.",
      "pos": [
        4600,
        4681
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Crash consistency",
      "pos": [
        4685,
        4702
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "No",
      "pos": [
        4705,
        4707
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This situation is equivalent to a virtual machine experiencing a \"crash\" (through either a soft or hard reset).",
      "pos": [
        4710,
        4821
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This typically happens when the Azure virtual machine is shut down at the time of backup.",
      "pos": [
        4822,
        4911
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For Azure virtual machine backups, getting a crash-consistent recovery point means that Azure Backup gives no guarantees around the consistency of the data on the storage medium--either from the perspective of the operating system or from the perspective of the application.",
      "pos": [
        4912,
        5186
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Only data that already exists on the disk at the time of backup is what gets captured and backed up.",
      "pos": [
        5187,
        5287
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While there are no guarantees, in most cases, the operating system will boot.",
      "pos": [
        5300,
        5377
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is typically followed by a disk-checking procedure, like chkdsk, to fix any corruption errors.",
      "pos": [
        5378,
        5477
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Any in-memory data or writes that have not been completely flushed to the disk will be lost.",
      "pos": [
        5478,
        5570
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The application typically follows with its own verification mechanism in case data rollback needs to be done.",
      "pos": [
        5571,
        5680
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As an example, if the transaction log has entries that are not present in the database, then the database software does a rollback until the data is consistent.",
      "pos": [
        5689,
        5849
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When data is spread across multiple virtual disks (like spanned volumes), a crash-consistent recovery point provides no guarantees for the correctness of the data.",
      "pos": [
        5850,
        6013
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Performance and resource utilization",
      "pos": [
        6020,
        6056
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Like backup software that is deployed on-premises, backing up VMs in Azure also needs to be planned for capacity and resource utilization.",
      "pos": [
        6057,
        6195
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Storage limits<ept id=\"p1\">](azure-subscription-service-limits.md#storage-limits)</ept> define how to structure VM deployments to get maximum performance with minimum impact to running workloads.",
      "pos": [
        6196,
        6383
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are two main Azure Storage limits that impact backup performance:",
      "pos": [
        6385,
        6456
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Max egress per storage account",
      "pos": [
        6460,
        6490
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Total request rate per storage account",
      "pos": [
        6493,
        6531
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Storage account limits",
      "pos": [
        6537,
        6559
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the backup data is copied out of the customer storage account, it counts towards the input/output operations per second (IOPS) and egress (storage throughput) metrics of the storage account.",
      "pos": [
        6560,
        6755
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "At the same time, the virtual machines are running and consuming  (IOPS) and throughput.",
      "pos": [
        6756,
        6844
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The goal is to ensure that the total traffic--backup and virtual machine--does not exceed the storage account limits.",
      "pos": [
        6845,
        6962
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Number of disks",
      "pos": [
        6968,
        6983
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The backup process is greedy and tries to consume as many resources as it can, with the aim of completing backup as quickly as possible.",
      "pos": [
        6984,
        7120
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, all I/O operations are limited by the <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Target Throughput for Single Blob<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, which has a limit of 60 MB per second.",
      "pos": [
        7121,
        7243
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In order to speed up the backup process, the backup of each disk of the VM is attempted <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>in parallel<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        7244,
        7346
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "So, if a VM has four disks, then Azure Backup will attempt to back up all four disks in parallel.",
      "pos": [
        7347,
        7444
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Because of this, the single most important factor that determines the backup traffic exiting from a customer storage account is the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>number of disks<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> being backed up from the storage account.",
      "pos": [
        7445,
        7638
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Backup schedule",
      "pos": [
        7644,
        7659
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An additional factor that impacts performance is the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>backup schedule<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        7660,
        7733
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you configure all the VMs to back up at the same time, then the number of disks being backed up <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>in parallel<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> will increase--as Azure Backup will attempt to back up as many disks as possible.",
      "pos": [
        7734,
        7928
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "So one way to reduce the backup traffic from a storage account is to ensure that different VMs are backed up at different times of the day, with no overlap.",
      "pos": [
        7929,
        8085
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Capacity planning",
      "pos": [
        8090,
        8107
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Putting all these factors together means that storage account usage needs to be planned properly.",
      "pos": [
        8108,
        8205
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Download the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>VM backup capacity planning Excel spreadsheet<ept id=\"p1\">](https://gallery.technet.microsoft.com/Azure-Backup-Storage-a46d7e33)</ept> to see the impact of your disk and backup schedule choices.",
      "pos": [
        8206,
        8395
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Backup throughput",
      "pos": [
        8401,
        8418
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For each disk being backed up, Azure Backup reads the blocks on the disk and stores only the changed data (incremental backup).",
      "pos": [
        8419,
